## 1. Executive Summary

A penetration test was conducted against the "Crocodile" host as part of the HackTheBox
Starting Point series. The engagement identified two exposed services — FTP (port 21) and
HTTP (port 80) — hosting a business website with an administrative login portal.

Testing revealed that the FTP service was misconfigured to permit **anonymous authentication**,
exposing files containing a list of usernames and their corresponding plaintext passwords.
These credentials were reused on the web application's administrative login page
(`login.php`), resulting in **unauthorized access to a privileged administrative dashboard**.

This engagement demonstrates a common real-world attack chain: a low-severity misconfiguration
(anonymous FTP) directly enabling a critical impact (full admin panel compromise) due to
credential reuse and lack of service segmentation.

**Overall Risk Rating: Critical**

