## 5. Attack Chain Summary

```
[1] Anonymous FTP login (port 21)
        │
        ▼
[2] Download allowed.userlist + allowed.userlist.passwd
        │
        ▼
[3] Identify privileged "admin" account + plaintext password
        │
        ▼
[4] Discover /login.php via directory brute-forcing
        │
        ▼
[5] Authenticate as admin → full administrative dashboard access
        │
        ▼
[6] Flag retrieved
```

This chain illustrates how a single low-friction misconfiguration (anonymous FTP) can cascade
into full administrative compromise when combined with poor credential hygiene.

---

## 6. Conclusion

The assessment successfully demonstrated that misconfigured anonymous FTP access, combined with
plaintext credential storage and credential reuse, allowed an unauthenticated attacker to gain
full administrative access to the target web application. Neither finding required advanced
tooling or exploitation skill — both were identified through standard reconnaissance and
enumeration practices, underscoring the real-world risk posed by basic service
misconfigurations. No further vulnerabilities were in scope for this engagement.

